            To do any operation we have operator and operand.

            Js operators are the symbols that perform operations on one or more operands and operands can be values or variables.


            In JS there are many categories of operators:

            1) Arithemetic Operators:
                i) Addition(+) -> 5 + 3  = 8
                ii) Subtraction(-) -> 5 - 3 = 2
                iii) Multiplication(*) -> 5 * 3 = 15
                iv) Division(/) -> 5 / 3 = 1.666
                v) Modulus(%) -> 5 % 3 = 2
                vi) Exponential -> 5**2 = 25

            2) Comparison Operators: The op of the comparison operators is boolean(true/false).
                i) Equal(==) -> 3 == '3' -> true
                ii) Not Equal (!=) -> 3!=4 -> true
                iii) Greater than (>) -> 3 > 1 -> true
                iv) Less than (<) -> 3 < 6 -> true
                v) Greater than or equal(>=) -> 3>=3 -> true
                vi) Less than or equal(<=) -> 3 <= 2 -> false
                vii) Strict equal (===) ->  3 === '3' -> false 
                viii) Strict not equal (!==) ->  3 !== '3' -> true

            3) Logical Operators: 
                    they take one or more values as input and gives boolean one value as output.
                i) AND(&&)-> if all the values are true then AND will return true.

                        truth table AND:
                     a          b       result
                    true      true      true
                    true      false     false
                    false     true      false
                    false     false     false

                ii) OR(||) -> if one of the value is true the result is true.

                        truth table OR:
                     a          b       result
                    true      true      true
                    true      false     true
                    false     true      true
                    false     false     false
                
                iii) NOT (!) -> NOT only takes one input and returns one output.

                            truth table NOT: 

                        a     result
                      true    false
                      false   true

        4) Ternary Operator: 
                (condition ? value1 : value2) -> if result of the condition is true the value1 will be returned and if result is false value2 is returned.

                ex: 5 > 3 ? "value is greater" : "value is smaller";

        5) Increment/decrement:
                These operators work on single operand.

            i) pre Increment:
            in pre Increment/decrement first the value gets changed and then used.
                var a = 10;
                a = a + 1; // 11
                ++a;  // a = a + 1;

            ii) post Increment:
            in post Increment first value gets used and then gets incremented.
                a++; // a = a + 1;


                var a = 100;
                var b = 200;
                var c = --a + b++ + --b + ++a;
                      99 + 200 + 200 + 100
                a 100
                b 200
                        

                console.log(a); 100, 100
                console.log(b); 200, 200
                console.log(c); 598, 599